and the goal is to provide the data science community with an overview of Posit Team.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
These demos are open to everyone, and the attendance over the past few months has been awesome,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
but feel free to share these webinars with your colleagues, friends,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
or anyone else that is looking to improve their own data science workflows with Posit Tools.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Now for this month's topic, we're going to focus on how to create a FastAPI in Python,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:07.000
and then show how this API can more or less build bridges between the various steps of your data science workflow.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Now before we dive into creating a FastAPI, let's quickly review Posit Team.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Posit Team is a bundled offering of our three professional data science tools,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Posit Workbench, Posit Connect, and Posit Package Manager.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Now taking a look at the diagram on your screen, we'll start at the very top with the data analyst,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
who will be writing code and creating insights using Posit Workbench.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
They can choose to write code in either R or Python, and they have a variety of IDEs to choose from,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.000
including RStudio, JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebooks, and VS Code.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:56.000
For R developers, they may be creating content such as Shiny applications, Pins, R Markdown, or Plumber APIs.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
And for Python developers, they may be creating content such as Flask, FastAPIs, Streamlit, Shiny,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
or Dash applications, Pins, or Jupyter Notebooks.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Once the content is created, the developers will need a way to easily share that content with the people that need to see it.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
And that's where Posit Connect comes into play.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Connect not only makes your content shareable, but also gives your team tight control over content access.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Finally, we have Posit Package Manager, which does exactly as its name implies,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
and that's to host, organize, and distribute open source R and Python packages,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
not only from the community, but also any internally developed R or Python packages.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:53.000
For today's workflow, we will use VS Code from within Posit Workbench to develop a FastAPI in Python.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And to keep things nice and simple, we're going to design this API to do only one thing, and that's to serve data.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
We'll then publish this FastAPI to Posit Connect and show how it can serve as a gateway to your data,

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:15.000
which can be accessed by multiple pieces of content using Python, R, or any other language or system.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Now, many of you may be like me, and when you started your data science journey,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
the idea of working with APIs, let alone creating your own API,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
was so daunting that I honestly tried to avoid working with APIs at all costs.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Well, I'm here to tell you that they're not that scary and can actually be used to vastly improve your data science workflows.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Now, the acronym API stands for Application Programming Interface,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
and they essentially allow communication between applications.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:56.000
To help explain what APIs are, I like to think of the commonly used restaurant analogy you see on your screen here.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Here we have three customers that have entered a restaurant

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
and would like to order some food that the chef in the kitchen will prepare.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
To request food, the customers need some way to communicate their order to the kitchen,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.000
and rarely, if ever, the customer will interact directly with the chef.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So that's where the waiter or waitress comes into play.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
They take the order from the customer and can communicate that order to the chef.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
The chef prepares the food, which is then delivered back to the customer.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So in this analogy, the waiter or waitress allows for communication between the customers and the chef.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Essentially, they are the API.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
For data scientists, APIs can be an essential workflow building block

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:50.000
that gives other users or applications or systems the ability to interact with the functions you've designed,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
the models you've trained, or the data you've curated.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.000
You also don't need to be a software engineer or computer scientist to create an API,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:06.000
and there are numerous frameworks in both R and Python for creating APIs, including Plumber and Flask.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
For today's workflow, we're going to focus on just FastAPI,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:15.000
which is one of the most popular frameworks for creating APIs using Python,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.000
given its simplicity and performance.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Now, as I previously mentioned, the FastAPI we are going to build today and publish to PositConnect

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
will essentially serve as a gateway to our data, which can be accessed by a variety of content.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
But why would you want to do this?

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Well, there are a few reasons.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The first reason is that it simplifies your code.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:45.000
You no longer need to attach and read in and transform the data into each individual piece of content.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
So this helps also prevent data duplication and also standardize data access across content.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Secondly, by putting data behind an API, it makes it easily accessible to different content types.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
For example, you can have a Jupyter Notebook built using Python

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.000
and a Shiny application built using R access the same data via the same API.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And later on in this demo, we'll demonstrate this capability.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
Lastly, by publishing the FastAPI to PositConnect,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.000
you can control access to your data by adding an authentication layer to your APIs.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And this is a great option if your team is working with sensitive data.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Now, we are very close to building our FastAPI,

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:38.000
but I just want to spend one minute and explain the data we're going to have behind this API.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
This data is completely made up, and I wanted to make it as simple as possible given our limited time today.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
Now, this data, it's also relatively small.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
It's only about 500 rows and has only two columns.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
The first column is a random letter in the English alphabet,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
and the second column is a random number from 1 to 20.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
And that's pretty much it.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
As we go through today's demo, I want you to think about where your data lives today.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
In this workflow, our data is going to live as a local CSV file,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
but maybe your data lives in a database or a shared network drive,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
or maybe as a pin on PositConnect.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
By using an API to access the data, no matter where it lives,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
we can standardize how the data is accessed across your various pieces of content

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.000
and your entire data science team.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Okay, so let's build our FastAPI.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:41.000
On this slide is all the code needed to create a simple data gateway FastAPI.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And as you can see, it's less than 20 lines of code.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:52.000
In the first three lines of code, we will import the libraries, modules, and functions needed for this workflow,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:58.000
including FastAPI itself, the typing module for hinting at content types,

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:04.000
and finally, the pandas library for reading in and manipulating our data.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
We next create the FastAPI instance using the FastAPI function,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
which we'll call app in this example.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Now, the first step of our API is to read in the data as a data frame

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
using the read CSV function from pandas.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:29.000
We'll then store our data frame as a variable called largeDF.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Next, we define our API endpoint.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Now, an endpoint takes in the API request, which is usually a URL,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
processes it, and sends back a response.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.000
For our FastAPI, we are using a get method for our endpoint,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
which is routinely used to read data.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:53.000
The forward slash followed by the word data tells the FastAPI

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
that anything following the forward slash data in the request URL

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:04.000
are parameters to the API, which can be fed into the function directly below.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And finally, we add the function itself.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
This is where all of the logic of your FastAPI lives.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:17.000
In our FastAPI, we are defining a single function called getFilteredData.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And it takes a single argument called letters.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.000
Letters are captured as a list of strings when the API is queried.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:32.000
It's also an optional query item and defaults to none if no letters are provided.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
So we next use the list of letters to filter our data.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And if I simply read this code left to right, top to bottom,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:46.000
we start by asking if the query contained any letters.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
If yes, the data is then filtered for those specific letters

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
and returned by the function.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
If no letters are provided, it simply returns the entire dataset itself.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
So now that we have all the code needed,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
I'm going to copy it to my clipboard

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.000
and then navigate over to Posit Workbench.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
So here's the homepage for Posit Workbench.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And you can see that I currently have three separate sessions running.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:23.000
I have a VS Code session, an RStudio session, and a Jupyter Notebook session.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
So I'm going to first navigate into this VS Code session,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
which I currently have open in another tab.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So I'll click on that.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And once here, you'll notice that I'm currently within a directory

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
I called FastAPIDemo.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And I previously created a virtual environment in this directory,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
which is called .venv.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And I'm first going to activate this virtual environment.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
So to do that, I'm going to open up a new terminal,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
click on these three lines in the top left corner,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
select Terminal and New Terminal.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
And once we have our prompt,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:00.000
I want to source the activate script within that virtual environment.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So venv bin activate and hit Enter.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Oops, spelled source wrong. Let's go ahead and fix that.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
And there we go. I now have my virtual environment activated.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
And this is typically best practice.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And it's a great idea just to ensure that the work we do here

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:25.000
is isolated from any other project currently on Posit Workbench.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
So let's go ahead and create a new Python file

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
by clicking the New File button,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.000
which you can find again clicking on these three lines, File, New File.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And I'm going to call this main.py and hit Enter.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
We're going to place it in our current working directory and hit OK.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
You can see it show up here on the File Explorer.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And now we have our file, which is completely empty.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And let's go ahead and paste in that FastAPI.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
So now that it's been created,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.000
let's go ahead and show you how to publish this FastAPI to Posit Connect

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
using the rsconnect Python package,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
which I previously installed into this environment.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
So the rsconnect Python package, it provides a command line interface,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
so you can use it within the terminal down here

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
for deploying content to Posit Connect.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So I'm going to type out the command here in the command line,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
and I'm going to explain each step along the way.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
So we first need to, I'll make my screen a little bit bigger here.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:34.000
We first need to tell rsconnect to deploy a FastAPI.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.000
Next, we need to indicate which Posit Connect instance

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
we will be deploying to.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Now, I previously saved this Connect instance into my environment,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
and I gave it the name pctprod.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:53.000
So all we need to do is give it the name dash n pctprod.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
And then finally, we just need to provide the name

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
and location of the FastAPI.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So this main file, it lives in my current working directory,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
which we can indicate with a period,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
and then we just have to provide the name of the file,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
hit enter, and that's pretty much it.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So this is going to kick off the publishing process.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
So the rsconnect Python package,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
it's essentially taking a snapshot of my environment,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
including what packages are in my environment, package versions,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
what Python version am I using.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:31.000
It sends that information from Posit Workbench to Posit Connect,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
and then it deploys this FastAPI.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And so we'll just give this a few more seconds to publish.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And there we go.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
So we're all done, and we get these two links down here,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
and so I'm going to go ahead and click on the dashboard content,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:59.000
and that will navigate us directly to Posit Connect.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
Now, once it's deployed,

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
we can now interact with this FastAPI on Connect

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
using this Swagger interface that you see on your screen.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
Our API, it only has one get endpoint,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
and we can try querying it using various letters in the alphabet

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
and seeing the resulting API response.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
So let's try querying this FastAPI

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
to extract all of the A rows in the dataset.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
So I'll select get right here, and we'll try it out.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And here we can add letters.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
So I'll add an A here, and then we can hit execute.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And once we hit execute, the Swagger interface,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:44.000
it'll show you the curl command that was run to ping the API,

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
the request URL, which is right here,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and then if we scroll down, we can see the response,

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
which is in this JSON format,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
where each row of the data is a chunk of this JSON file.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
Let's try a few different combinations

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:02.000
just to make sure that the API is behaving correctly.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So let me come back up here to the top,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
and we'll add an additional string item.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
So maybe we'll do, let's try T,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
and we'll also try M, hit execute,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
and we can see the curl response, the request URL,

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
and here we can see the response,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
where it's just Ts and Ms.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
Now, a major benefit of this API hosted on Deposit Connect

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
is that you can manage who has access to it,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
which is shown right over here.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.000
If I select any of the options that require authentication,

